
Considered (by FreeCodeCamp) to be the most popular JavaScript tool "of all time."



Adding jQuery
    1. Same as adding JavaScript, place within a "script" block 
        >> <script></script>
    2. Next, within the script block, add the jQuery format
        >> $(document).ready(function() {  });
        - Without this "document ready" signification, the script may try to run before the HTML



Adding functionality: .addClass*()
    1. The 'Bling' sign ($) proceeds every jQuery operation
        - This goes inside the document-ready block
    2. '.addClass' function allows you to add functionality to a page element

    - Making an element 'bounce'
        >> $("button").addClass("animated bounce");
    - Shake
        >> $("button").addClass("animated shake");
    - FadeOut
        >> $("#target6").addClass("animated fadeOut");
    - Hinge
        >> $("body").addClass("animated hinge");

    3. Any class or id can be selected using their css designations
        >> .menu-item // #bottom-button
    4. Also able to add Bootstrap qualities to your jQuery
        >> $("#target1").addClass("btn-primary");



Removing functionality: .removeClass // .remove()
    - You can remove functionality with 'removeClass' instead
        >> $("#target2").removeClass("btn-default");
    2. Remove something altogether with '.remove()'
        >> $("#target4").remove();



Changing the CSS: .css()
    1. Change the CSS on an element with '.css()'
        >> $("#target1").css("color", "blue");
        -- This changes the target1 id to a color of blue



Property Change: .prop()
    - Change the property with '.prop()'
        >> $("button").prop("disabled", true);
        -- This disables any button divs 



HTML Change: .html() // .text() // .appendTo() // .clone()
    1. Add HTML within an element 
        >> $("h3").html("<em>jQuery Playground</em>");
    2. Add text within an element; this will also be replacing any text that is already present within the div
        >> $("h3").text("Here's your sign!");
    3. Moving elements with '.appendTo()'
        >> $("#target4").appendTo("#left-well");
        -- This removes the element and pastes it within another
    4. Copy / Paste is possible with '.clone()'
        >> $("#target2").clone().appendTo("#right-well");
        -- To use properly you'll have to first clone then 'appendTo'

Parent and Children Change: .parent() // .children()
    1. This allows for the selection of the parent of whatever element you choose
        >> $("#left-well").parent().css("background-color", "blue")
    2. The child selection will select everything within a certain div
        >> $("#left-well").children().css("color", "blue")
    
Special child-selector: ".target:nth-child()" // ".target:odd"
    1. This allows for the sepecific selection
        >> $(".target:nth-child(3)").addClass("animated bounce");
    2. Select the even or odd with special selector
        >> $(".target:odd").addClass("animated shake");

Target Body: $("body")
    1. Update the body of your HTML 
        >> $("body").addClass("animated fadeOut");